column1: By when will more than 15,000,000 COVID-19 tests have been conducted in the United States?

15 M tests have been conducted on May 26th

The outcome of this one hasn't been in doubt for a few weeks; we passed 15M tests today. But the numbers for the past two days have been on the low side. If this dip had happened earlier it could have moved the finish line into June. It just goes to show that it doesn't pay to ever be too certain.

The number of tests has risen almost exactly along the trajectory I predicted 2 weeks ago with a linear increase in new tests per day and a parabolic increase in total tests. According to my equation, May 27 will be the first day with 15 million tests. Even if the number of new tests per day remains fixed at this point, 15 million will be surpassed by the end of May. Since this is very close to the end of June and there remains a chance of a testing slowdown, I am increasing my confidence but still keeping it below 90%.

Need 274,013 tests per day on average from now until the end of May to have 15 million. Over the past two weeks, the average is roughly 289,000, and in just the past week it is 316,000. Add in the fact that every politician is incentivized to increase testing to re-open safely, and before May 31 is a fairly safe bet.

It is unlikely the rate of testing will decrease as there are still more people who need a test than can get one. Therefore reaching the 15 million milestone before July and August is virtually certain. If the rate of testing per day continues to increase linearly, as it has roughly done so far, then over 15 million tests will be completed by the end of May. Continued increasing in the number of tests seems most likely.

Currently the U.S. is conducting 1.5/2 million tests per week and is planning to double its capacity in the coming weeks. Assuming that tests are still in production for 3 weeks and that during those 3 weeks the average conducted tests are 1.75 million, we reach May 16th with a total of 10.5 million tests conducted in total. One factor we have to take into consideration is that the costs of these tests are decreasing, or at least they will be, and they will be made more accessible. The combination of easier accessibility, lower cost, and increased screening lead me to believe that the U.S. will pass 15 million testa by the end of May. However, having seen the lack of a national guideline on testing different perspectives may slow down testing and its efficiency which is why also consider the first week and a half a plausible date for the passing of the threshold.

Interesting Politico Live Tracker: https://www.politico.com/interactives/2020/coronavirus-testing-by-state-chart-of-new-cases/ However from The Atlantics and Stat News above, it seems that a variety of obstacles can hinder a continuation of the testing trend (roughly locating 15M somewhere in June), let alone an exponential growth of the number of tests conducted.

The main is that at this point COVID Tracking Project is tracking RNA testing of SARS-CoV-2. This forecast takes into account only this kind of testing. My assumption is that over late spring and summer, number of tests, which is now based mostly on testing moderate to severe COVID conditions, will be going down due to social distancing and, to lesser extent, seasonal nature of coronavirus. My estimate is that the number of tests (according to my logistic model) will be between 6 to 7 million. The real number of infections, if asymptomatic and mild cases are included, of course, is much higher, but due to limiting factors - number of kits, equipment, PPE, trained lab personnel... - it is not reflected in number of performed tests.
The US Government is not perpared for this scale - especially not Mr. Trump.

There are lots of logistics that have to be in place to enable more testing -- swabs, test kits, chemical reagents, laboratories, and skilled lab technicians. If any one is missing the test rate cannot increase. The number of tests was increasing at a fast exponential rate (nearly doubling every 2 days) throughout the month of March, until the 27th. Since then the rate of increase has slowed, but it's still going up. It seems unlikely that 15M tests will be done by May 1, so I'll go with the crowd and wager a 2% chance.

Currently the average number of tests is growing at a (smoothed) ~5% p.d. though this has been rapidly dropping as absolute numbers grow. This models an exponential decay from ~5% going forward with the number of tests per day peaking around ~300k (assumes no upper limits on capacity below this mark) at the end of May / beginning of June and ~0.2% growth at this time.

Para el día 30 de marzo “… the United States had just run five tests per million” teniendo un total de 328,2 millones de habitantes en el país el año 2019. Eso equivale a un total de 1641 tests efectuados. Sin embargo, hay que tener en cuanta que el país no estaba trabajando con su máximo potencial en torno a esta enfermedad. Además, el día 28 de marzo se anunció que desde una semana más adelante se "... espera la fabricación de cerca de cinco millones de test al mes”. Por lo tanto, suponiendo que estos tests logran ser producidos y utilizados en el país, en menos de tres meses (abril, mayo y junio) el país habría superado la realización de 15 millones de tests. Sin embrago, como se podría estar tanto subestimando la capacidad de desarrollo de tests de corona virus, como sobrestimando, no puedo atribuirle todas las probabilidades de cumplir con los 15 millones de tests de corona virus al mes de junio.
